No liberating amendment for Tymozhenko by Parliament
The Ukrainian parliament today denied the request to abolish, as part of an amendment to the Criminal Code, those clauses on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko had been convicted.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the liberation of the imprisoned ex-premier minister, was rejected by MEPs at the second reading of the request to mitigate the penalties for economic crimes.
Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for the conclusion of an allegedly negative contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet final, the appeal of the convicted is to be brought to court in December.
Timoshenko himself describes the verdict as political revenge of the regime and also in the West, the trial raised suspicion of the bias of the court.
The request to remove Section 365, on the basis of which the Prime Minister was convicted, from the Criminal Code, was supported by 147 MPs.
226 votes would have been required for its adoption.
