IBM history: From cheese cutters to spaceflights
Founded a hundred years ago in New York, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM only in 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone for the later IBM company was the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They had technologies such as the famous clocks for the registration of the start and end of work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who was also Chairman of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competition company Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
This leader then even eclipsed the founders of IBM - based on Watson's ideas to this day the invincible culture and identity of the company.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began with the production and distribution of all possible machines for trade - from sausage and cheese cutters, to cash registers.
In the first four decades in which Watson ran the company, he doubled its revenues to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the executive chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers from IBM helped NASA direct flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn and in 1969 also the famous flight of man to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC, which determined the computer standard of that time, came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consultant part of the PricewaterhouseCoopers company and thus entered fully into the consulting services and services business with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the last three years is the "Smarter Planet" concept.
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas not even planned so far, e.g. to improve the situation in transport and in city management.
In the retail sector, IBM recently introduced the Smart Commerce platform to help traders manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
In 1932 IBM founded a branch in the then Czechoslovakia - the first country in Central and Eastern Europe at all.
Today IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe are located in Prague and here is also a top research team of world level that deals with voice recognition technology.
