21er Haus in Vienna
The Moved Pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with highs, lows and happy ending: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion of Brussels won prizes in 1958, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and disappeared.
Now it is reopened as an exhibition house.
If modern post-war architecture is enthralled by clear shapes, glass halls, bold turns and new building materials typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion of architect Karl Schwacker is an apt and famous example of the 1958 World Exhibition in Brüssler.
At the time, Dicker's pavilion received the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its light and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still considered a milestone of contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so famous that he also built Austria's pavilion at the next World's Fair.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus a bowl-like extension in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, was set up in the Swiss Garden near the Vienna South Railway Station after the World Exhibition, rebuilt and opened a museum of the 20th century in 1962 - the "20er Haus" was called it.
However, the building was neither spatial nor technical as a museum - no walls to hang the art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art got a new house in Vienna.
Since 2001, the building was empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called the "21er Haus" and will be used as a museum for contemporary art in the future.
Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a stroke of luck in every respect.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Österreichische Galerie Belvedere in 2007, has completed the new start.
Husslein-Arco, an art historian with a remarkable career, among other things, in his youth as an figure skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, implemented the transformation strongly among politicians and conservationists, procured public funds and private sponsorship funds and determined the use.
Besides contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, a café and a bookstore should be there, and an office building had to be built.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the execution then Krischanitz was the ideal occupation.
Not only because he had sensitively rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied at the Technical University of Vienna with Schwecker and the pavilion was a "unfortunately important place" for him, where he had watched the exhibitions "almost every weekend".
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which already lost in generosity and ease when he moved to Vienna and its conversion.
With the current reconstruction, there were far greater problems: the building was "an energy hurler," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facade were replaced, glass-fiber-reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel beams have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been renovated.
Two basements brought space for the new use, a lowered light ditch between house and street provides for the exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light tail pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old red-brown rust protection color.
And the cinema room is still exactly the same as it used to be.
And all under strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found that is good and cheap and also liked the Heritage Office," says Krischanitz, pointing to a rough ground in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and modifications, the building has remained flexible and lightweight.
It had been difficult with the pavilion "which came from Brussels", Krischanitz recently said, a typical "drop-in-the-city story".
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and nevertheless wants to "awaken a real consciousness".
In this case, however, the 21er Haus is not in the wrong place, because there has been a lucky urban development case: Around the Swiss garden, the completely newly planned "Hauptbahnhofsquartier", with office and residential buildings, is being created.
And another stroke of luck may still occur: The 21er Haus could get reinforcement from another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin Temporary Kunsthalle, and as you can hear, she is already negotiating with the city for a neighbourly location in the Swiss Garden.
