Smart crows spread in cities
In many places seed crows are regarded as "problem birds": But the highly intelligent animals can no longer be driven out of the cities, experts claim.
Some like it, others want to get rid of it very quickly: crows have been part of the cityscape for centuries, but in many municipalities local residents' complaints about the dirt and noise of animals are piled up.
A remedy against the "problem birds" is not yet in sight.
Seed crows can no longer be retrieved from the cities, experts said at the first crow symposium in the East Frisian void.
There, experts from all over Germany discussed possible ways out.
You are looking for alternatives in the cities
Nature conservationists also attributed the problems in cities to the rural exodus of the particularly protected seed crows: the use of chemicals in agriculture is increasingly destroying traditional habitats.
Hunting, growing cultivation, and the fall of typical breeding trees made life difficult for birds.
Crows are protected.
Large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs exist in the Westphalian Soest, in the northwest among others in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen as well as in Leer.
There in 2005 a controversial project for the mass killing of crows in the district had caused negative headlines.
Critics had described the capture of animals in bird traps and the killing with clubs as particularly brutal.
"The normal expulsion, the excavation, does nothing," the city and landscape planner Werner Klöver from Leer noted.
Spraying away nests with water or cutting down trees often has undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
"The animals escape, large colonies split up and spread elsewhere."
It is only possible to bury them as an exception to hospitals, nursing homes or schools.
"We have to live with them, we can't get them away."
Without the surrounding area, the problem cannot be solved in the cities, said Mayor Wolfgang Kellner from Leer.
It is conceivable that a combination of animal burials from sensitive living areas and lock offers could be used to resettle them in other places.
On the other hand, the psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens advocated "information boards instead of chain saws" for an entirely different way of dealing with the animals: "After all, we can best bear a pimple on the face confidently."
Jürgens had co-founded the Aschenberger Krähen educational trail in Schleswig-Holstein, where signs inform about the life of the highly intelligent seed crows.
The project is already being accepted by tourists.
Jürgens also had his own opinion on the criticism of the birds' noise: "There is a lot of communication, they have a lot to say."
The intelligence and skill of the animals are legendary: Seed crows not only use tools to get a treat, but even produce their own tools as aids.
Behavioural researchers at the University of Cambridge recently tested on four seed crows how far the intelligence of the birds reaches.
In an experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to use stones to bring a scaffold to collapse in order to reach a moth larva.
Without much training, they determined what size and shape a stone must have in order to cause the platform to collapse.
In a second attempt, the clever crows had to solve a more tricky problem.
In a vertical cylinder, the researchers had placed a small bucket with a moth larve.
With the beak the birds could not reach their prey.
However, the researchers had laid down pieces of wire for them.
From this all four animals formed a hook, with the help of which they then fished the bucket on the handle out of the tube.
Three of the four seed crows managed to do so immediately.
