Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Watch You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many guys who broadcast their anti-immigration opinion online.
On Monday, Breivik, who confessed to having committed an amok run in Norway in July, in which 77 people were killed, had his first public hearing in court.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is by far not alone in cyberspace: he has spent a lot of time before his attack in front of his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on the side of social networks.
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
This is easy - you only have to log in to Facebook.
"We have found that it wasn't difficult to get to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by the British idea factory DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook's hiding of personal data is so encyclopaedic, Bartlett says, that researchers simply need to use the page's advertising tool to accurately define their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy - as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then targeted them with add-ons, but instead of linking to a new band or a new diet product, the Adds invited users to a survey asking for their level of education, attitude to violence and assessment of their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to question more than 10,000 supporters of 14 highly right-wing parties in 11 European countries - without even having to leave their office once.
"It's a fairly new research method," says Bartlett.
Some of the results hardly surprise. Online supporters of far-right groups are mostly young, male and annoyed about immigration.
But in a sort of surprising twist, "those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screens."
DEMO's work is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Ideas factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends such as "likes", text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three content per day, Facebook's "Data Supernova" generates a research boom that has increased the number of scientific work with the name of this page in the title by nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that through this page you can study people that you don't normally reach with your clipboard on the street.
"If you used to try to question people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"They first had to inform the party and it would never have allowed them access," says Bartlett.
"On Facebook, it's all gone - you're going straight to them."
Others say that the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
