Stories about cheating in school and college exams are widespread.
There have been incidents in which teachers have given their students the exam answers so that they were good at their performance checks themselves.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
Studies show that every day we lie between 10 and 200 times.
But many of these lies are regarded as a lie of necessity.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognising lies or "uncovering lies" is one that is important for everyone, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game such as Scharaden, in which the goal is to call "Have You!", demasking a deception is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have carried out far-reaching research projects, particularly in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been exposed.
Lies look you in the eye.
They stutter, stammer, blush, and do not always falter.
However, it cannot be concluded from this that these liars are difficult to discover and to expose.
A trained liar can penetrate to the truth by learning something about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, about questioning and timing.
I have spent several years studying the scientific results of the comprehensive and ever-growing area of defiling. And it is clear that defiling a deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps us to find justice in our complex world, especially when hiring or questioning persons or negotiations or administration is one of our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at appreciating other people, raising their interest and mastering their own emotions, and they intuitively feel how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverted people lie more often than introverted people that men are more often "self-directed" lies than women whose lies are more "orientated" - as a rule, they want to protect the feelings of others - that married people lie less frequently to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are usually "fat lies").
We also know that when a person is exposed as an evildoer, others feel less guilty of lying to that person.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First of all, by observing the normal behavior of this person.
It's called "baselining," the starting position.
It provides a reference point for the subsequent assessment of changes.
Watch the posture, the laughter, the voice quality of your subject.
You should better know when someone usually keeps jumping with the foot, so they don't blame him wrongly when he's tripping with the foot during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of conspicuous verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
Think of these accumulations as alarm bells that shrill, not as proof of a disguise.
People who deceive may freeze when they try to remember their story. Maybe their feet point towards the door or they lean toward the exit, change their position in a significant way or show a "relaxation after the interview", this deep, relaxing exhalation and the change in posture when all the hard questions are over.
Questioners often falsely signal that an interview is over just to look for this relaxation after the interview.
Also pay attention to the language of your subject.
The slip of Scott Peterson is famous when he used the past form when he claimed his killed wife was still alive and triggered a national search for her.
Disappointing people can also use a distant language: "I had no sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or if one repeats a tricky question in the whole.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when they answer a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth ... as far as I know ... to the best of my knowledge and conscience."
This makes the answer more perceptive than objective, which often makes the alarm bells shrill.
There is no magic tool to expose lies, but you can learn skills that allow for demasking.
These skills make it easier for anyone to become a victim of fraud, both in private and professional life.
