Climatic adversity slowed down the economy
In the first year in which Mario López Valdez is in government, unemployment and undeclared work rose in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa. It is the first year in which Mario López Valdez, who describes himself as the initiator of the change and fostered great hopes for economic growth, is in government. However, due to climatic adversity, growth cannot be mentioned, but on the contrary, the main economic indicators worsened.
The low temperatures in February not only caused losses of millions in agriculture, but also narrowed the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first quarter of the year.This is mainly due to the historic decline in agricultural development of 31.16 percent, which slowed down further economic sectors.
According to a report published by Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development), 582 000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, 78.03 percent of which were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity up to November has caused unemployment to rise steadily in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter of the year, as from January to March 55,053 inhabitants of Sinaloa had no employment, which corresponds to 4.53% of the labour force. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28% and from July to September to 6.19%, resulting in 74 000 unemployed in Sinaloa, which is 18,969 more than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
The unemployment in Sinaloa in the year goes back to several factors. Economic scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments that the politics of public institutions indirectly explain the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently seeing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Among other things, liquidity losses in the market as a result of the cutbacks in funding from legislation adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who are illegally accumulating dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them, or use them for anything else," he explained.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country looking for work abroad, especially in the United States, has decreased, due on the one hand to the problems of entry and, on the other hand, because it is also difficult to find work there. These people stay here looking for work here, which causes unemployment to rise," he says.
undeclared work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious if the high proportion of undeclared work is taken into account. According to INEGI, this includes 60.38 percent of the employees working in the country without paying into the social security funds.
Unemployment and undeclared work come from low wages, the lowest in Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Security Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Agency for Labour and Social Welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of employees in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos by September, much less than the general government average of 7375 pesos.
Decrease in FDI
In addition to reducing economic activity and increasing unemployment, the largest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) in the last ten years is recorded in 2011. According to Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the FDI amounted to $630,597 between January and June, corresponding to a decline of 87.74 percent compared to the $5 143,312 in the same period in the previous year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Agency for Economic Development) for its part recorded a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt
In view of the economic crisis, in July the state government applied to the National Congress for a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities to reactivate the economy. The state congress approved an amount of 200 600 000 pesos, but no positive effects of debt on any of the country’s economic sectors could be identified by November.
Reactions
For the representatives of the entrepreneurship, the first year of government made Mario López Valdé's government incapacity obvious.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of Manufacturing Industry in Mexico), argued that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonise the views of the different sectors, including the state government.
"Economic activity in Sinaloa was really poor this year, and it needs to be worked hard to regain the terrain lost this year, and in 2012 we have to make a double effort. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the government team that has already been well tuned to each other, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López stated that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year made the country's economic development more difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important effects is a slowed economy that is not in motion enough to create an economic dynamic that could generate an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. Therefore, we will complete the year well below our expectations," he said.
Redefining appointment
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Mexico Business Association) in Sinaloa, said that it was necessary to make the state more productive.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redefine the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all material and human resources of Sinaloa," he said.
There's a lot to do
The chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that will guide the government's efforts in a better direction.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
"There are areas where one can say that the government has acted more comprehensively. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
