The court approves the transition to digital television in Mexico in 2015
The transition of analogue to digital signals has been one of the most important changes worldwide in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) rejected the constitutional actions filed by the Senate and the House of Deputies against the Presidential Decree, and by virtue of which the switching from analogue to digital signals from 2021 to 2015 must be brought forward, due to the lack of eight votes required to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including Supreme Court President Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his responsibilities when he issued the legislative decree detailing the switchover to terrestrial digital television.
This resolution rejected the constitutional dispute created by the Senate because it did not receive the required qualified majority of eight votes so that the court could decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality. Thus, the law remains in force.
In the project for the lawsuit prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, it was proposed that the decree of law be declared unconstitutional, since the regulations relating to radio and television are the responsibility of the Comisión Federal de Telecommunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico), which is why the decree of law would be contrary to hierarchical principles and the provisions of the law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the decree of law. After the lawsuits were accepted, Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer applied the decree of law and ceased all activities to establish the digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the complaint submitted by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the debate on the project, which was also the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree with the project's arguments, in the sense that the national government should not regulate the measures that the public administration should take under general rules.
"I don't think that if you did that, the independence of the regulatory body would be compromised." She also recalled that the central government is responsible for planning strategic policies, such as the telecommunications sector, for constitutional reasons, because it manages state affairs.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital is one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years around the world, and it causes better use of the radioelectric spectrum, an increased quality of signal and more channels.
The postponement of the changeover, she said, was a postponement of the exploitation of digitalisation, which was a decision in the public interest that had not only technical aspects, "because they encompass economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she stressed, "made the action of the entire system necessary, according to the principle of economic governance by the state, they included a group of features that put the constitution in the hands of the central government."
She recalled that many countries around the world had already implemented the digital transition, through the government, even though they had highly specialised facilities.
It could not be concluded that with the publication of the contested decree of law, the government intervened in the powers of Congress, because the laws adopted by the legislature were respected," she assured.
The possibility to count the ballots in Michoacán individually is being considered
