In this sense, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just last November 9th the polling post adopted a series of rules to harmonise local rules with the reforms of the states in electoral matters.
It should be remembered that Michoacán had not adapted his political constitution, election law, or election justice law to the reforms adopted by Congress, so that they had not entered into force during this election round. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the state scoreboard within the time limits set for that, arguing nor having objections to it.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) ruled on the constitutional action filed by the local legislature and judged the State Commissioner's vote on the constitutional reforms as "invalid and unlawful", as he did not have the right to "decide or veto it".
María de los Ángeles Llanderal, in an interview on the possibility of individual counting of votes, stated that, thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by Consejo General del IEM, there is now the possibility that the local electoral authority could count the ballots in part or in full.
Under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be partially counted.The results in the minutes do not agree; the minutes on the counting and calculation of votes are not available on the record, or are not in the possession of the chairman of the electoral committee, or there are obvious errors or amendments in the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the fully filled-in ballots can be made if there is a difference between the alleged winner and the person in second place, which is equal to or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an explicit request from the party or coalition chairman, who is the second of the candidates mentioned.
The vote count may also be made in its entirety if, after completion of the ordinary calculation, it is established that the difference between the alleged winner and the candidate in second place is equal or less than one percent, provided that an explicit application is made by a party representative whose candidate has finished second. In this case, the electoral packages that have been suspended from a partial counting would be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that the elections are in the same situation in Morelia, where, according to PREP, the difference between first and second place is just under 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 voting protocols have not yet been counted.
