Some of the greatest shows we've put down in the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We played on some huge shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that they made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
Really, we feel like playing there.
We love this country, we like to surf and are excited about the jungle. Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo, where the waves are simply unimaginable.
My friends have always gone to Costa Rica and Nicaragua for surfing. Together with Mexico, these are excellent areas for surfing. In this way, we learned about people who love surfing.
With a look at the tour you have offered huge shows with many songs.
What plans do you have for the event in Costa Rica?
Since we have never played there, we also set ourselves no limits.
We will try to give the best possible show with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why?
I think that's partly because we have nine records and can play over 120 songs. Everyone likes a different song, so the decision we're going to play is not easy.
If we record two or three songs that we haven't played for a long time, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs. Otherwise, they might be forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us and I think that's why it's also for the audience.
With this tour you are celebrating your twenty-year history.
When you look back, is it hard for you to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I don't think any of us imagined playing in a great rock band for more than 20 years. It seems like a dream.
We continue to rely on this blessing and find it great to be able to make music together even now.
We like each other and are thrilled to produce music.
We are lucky to be able to drive to the places in the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't be any better.
What did it mean for you to have actively participated in the birth of the grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of big bands.
We're good friends with Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and abundantly unusual when a movement emerges from a group of friends.
Every now and then a band comes out of a city, but it is unusual when five or ten groups come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on their tour. We are still looking forward to being friends with them all and it honors us to be part of this emerging Seattle sound.
It is also very unusual that a band like yours stayed together with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago. This alone is a lot more time than many bands outlast.
First of all, I believe that we are all happy to be alive and also to take care of each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up, giving each individual the freedom to experiment.
One trusts the other and his music. We couldn't get any better.
Your relationship with fame has not always been easy, but on the other hand, thanks to your success, you could always do what you wanted.
How do you find a balance?
The way we grew has made it easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure not to be on tour too often, because it is too easy to fall into this game with huge crowds of people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people came for the music, that reminds you that you have to watch the music and what it has brought into being, without being obsessed with being a famous rock star. We never cared about that anyway.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and at the beginning it was great.
We were a band for three years that had never released a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed to have taken so long. We are still good with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who built up the band with us, friends. When I hear a song or see photos, I think about what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh. It was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh together and talk about music and football and many other topics.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The domestic band Las Robertas are responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why the band chose for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos from several groups and we liked this band the best. Therefore, we are curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live.
Why do you always change Yellow Ledbetter's lyrics when you play live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing he can think of.
Who influenced you as a bassist?
Of so many+
The first to come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive, even though it is no longer a fad?
I think we all don't feel very attached to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I think of the bands I mentioned before, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came up at the same time. If they are still important today, I think that's great, because it's worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney are making better music now than ever before.
At first her music was darker, now she's more positive.
Why?
This is interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a little frivolous, but there are other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive in themselves.
The tears came to me when I heard Ed playing them. They are very dark songs.
I think when you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life - for example when you lose a family member or a friend - that influences your artistic creation and your music and these two songs clearly embody this for me.
But I also think that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
Peru:
Fujimori returned to hospital for medical examination
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to investigate the muscle loss of his legs, his family doctor informed.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who serves 25 years in prison for violation of human rights during his reign (1990-2000), has several diseases, including tongue cancer, which operates four times and is under control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, congressman and his personal doctor, told television that Fujimori would be examined for three days at the Peruvian hospital Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas to determine the reason for his pain and muscle loss in the lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons. Nevertheless, he did not wish for this because he considered him innocent.
He was operated on four times on tongue cancer and he lost 18 kilos of weight. In addition, there are other diseases such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and blood circulation problems in the legs, the doctor counted.
Fujimori has been in the Dirección Nacional de Operaciones Especiales de la policía detention centre since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the Peruvian Army's death squad, which was secretly active during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official delegation, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and composed of several ministers and entrepreneurs, will start their visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues of the region.
Mujica will meet with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón next Wednesday. According to the Uruguayan president, this will be the highlight of his booked-up schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico.
The meeting of both presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for exchanging information on all policy areas between the two countries," the South American country's presidential office announced on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calderón's support for the incident with France when French head of government Nicolas Sarkozy placed the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his discourse, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that still act as tax havens. This statement was rejected by Uruguay and prompted a request from his ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has chaired the G20 since November, a group of the world’s most powerful emerging and industrialised countries. Since January of this year, there has been an agreement on the exchange of tax information to avoid double taxation with the South American country.
In recent years, the Government of Uruguay has sought to accelerate the concretization of tax information exchange agreements in order to be removed from the "grey list" of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), which is the focus of countries that have not introduced all international standards for tax cooperation.
Since 2004, there has been a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay, which has contributed to a growing trade in goods between the two countries.
The purr-beard installer enters the third dimension with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought tirelessly for 25 years for the rescue of Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but never in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he fights for the love of the girl in stereo technology.
The game that comes this month to the store counters all over the world has been tailored from the beginning to the features of the Nintende 3DS portable console, with which you can play three-dimensionally without special glasses.
"Mario is the figure who has to say how stereoscopy works without glasses," assured Omar Álvarez, the person responsible for the Nintendo-specialized press in Spain, at the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first Nintendo video game developed from the beginning for this console" because until now, success articles such as "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" have been adaptations of existing titles.
Nintendo's spokesman underlined that although it was three-dimensional, "Super Mario 3D Land" was an "affordable" video game that allowed a fast, liquid game.
Álvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" contained two games in one: the first part is "light" to capture the less tasted users.
After that, the experts can turn a "second round" over the different game levels, which are becoming increasingly difficult.
In addition, users can choose between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action in real time. However, in order to overcome the obstacles without becoming victims of the "optical effects", they always have to play three-dimensionally.
This trip of Super Mario into the three-dimensional world also means the return of the figure to a portable console, which has not been the case since 2005.
With this video game, Nintendo winks at the fans of the Saga and repeats the recipe for success of recent editions: The purr-beard installer must overcome dangerously-picked platforms to free Princess Peach.
However, the player encounters news in movements, the environment, disguises and enemies - and a "playable" Luigi.
Colom warrants the extradition of Portillo to the United States
The President of Guatemala, Álvaro Colom, announced this Tuesday that he would allow the extradition of former Governor Alfonso Portillo, so that he would be responsible in the United States for the conspiracy to money-launder US$70 million.
Thus the trial of the U.S. application for extradition of Portillo ends, so that it can be brought to justice there.
In a press conference, Colom confirmed his decision on the independence of judicial authority and government, taking into account that a decision-making court had already ordered extradition.
He stressed that he had not interfered with court decisions during his government and had accepted all extradition requests he was notified of.
Apart from Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín is extradited for murder and serious assault, Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
Colom's action is a government act that takes place when all judicial and constitutional bodies are exhausted to condemn the former President of the State (2000-2004).
According to the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court of Guatemala, Portillo must be extradited when his legal situation in Guatemale is clarified and his human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted for embezzling 120 million Quetzales in the Ministry of Defence during his reign. This trial preceded extradition, but the minister filed a protest and revived the case.
Trinijove has helped 6000 young people at risk of social exclusion
The organisation was set up to avoid the marginalisation of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of life of the social assistance organisation Trinijove have led to important results: in this quarter century, 6000 young people threatened with social exclusion were supported to find a way out of their difficult situation.
In addition, there are over a hundred jobs created for this social group.
On the occasion of the anniversary, an event was held yesterday in the former factory buildings of Fabra i Coats, attended by more than 300 people.
Trinijove was launched in 1986 in the district of Trinitat Vella with the aim of helping young people with low levels of education, without work, with drug problems at risk of marginality.
Yesterday's celebration in Sant Andreu was attended by a large number of those in charge of institutions and institutions working with the association during these 25 years.
The participation of political representatives from different directions during campaign times demonstrated the impartiality of the work done by Trinijove.
Besides the president of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol participated in the celebrations of the former socialist minister of education Ernest Maragall and the former mayor and currently left-green city councillor Ricard Goma.
The large hall of Fabra i Coats was also visited by the current Catalan Minister for Social Affairs and the Family, Josep Lluís Cleries, and Jaume Lanaspa, Director General of the Sparkasse La Caixa Social Works.
Mas stressed that Trinijove was launched in very difficult times and that today's times are no less complicated, but he added that the work done so far is "a good basis".
For the President of the Generalitat, Trinijove is an example that knows how to fight against difficult circumstances and gives hope to people in trouble.
"The economic crisis is nothing new for the association and the work it does," he explained.
Occupied house where giant parties were held was vacated
The homeowners had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building on Balmes No. 51 (Barcelona).
The twelve squatters left the building yesterday afternoon without resisting.
Everything indicates that the nightmares of the neighbors of house No. 51 on the street Balmes have ended.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building, which they had illegally occupied and in which they had organized huge festivals that had driven the neighborhood to despair. The eviction was carried out by judicial order without police intervention.
After the eviction, the door lock was changed to avoid a similar situation.
"As of now, access will be controlled," confirmed the house manager.
The squatters, who occupied 11 of the building's 13 apartments - the rest were inhabited - took with them the entire electrical system and part of the water supply. They also painted the walls and left behind all kinds of garbage, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
On the three lower floors huge parties were celebrated, which lasted up to two days and drove the tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which also suffered damage from it.
Her owner, Maria Pantinat, explained to Europa Press that her business had decreased by 80% since the beginning of the occupation.
The owner of the discotheque pointed out that the squatters made their unfair competition, because they sold the drinks to three euros, while they cost 10 euros in the discotheque.
In addition, the owner of the leisure restaurant had been reported by the neighbors for disturbance of rest, while according to her statement the noise did not come from the visitors of the disco, but from the squatters, and in particular from the guests of the festivals organized there, and which, according to the angered neighbors, became more and more and longer in recent weeks.
The head of the discotheque stated that the harassment had been so great that it agreed with the owner of the building that no rent had to be paid for the last nine months.
Guardia Urbana (urban police) also confirmed that she had received more complaints from the neighbors in recent weeks.
Last week, the chairman of the PP (Partido Popular - People's Party) in the Barcelona City Council, Alberto Fernández Díaz, called for the building to be evacuated immediately and the problems of civil coexistence and the decline of the neighbourhood to be tackled.
He explained that only one floor of the building had been occupied before the summer, but that the squatters had advanced to all floors of the building and almost all the apartments in the last few months. In some, even theft had occurred.
In this sense, he added that "it is necessary to put an end to impunity and to take action against the anti-social acts in the building."
Yesterday, another building in the Nou Barris district was evacuated by the Catalonian police.
At 3.30 p.m., police approached Montral No. 35 after receiving a call from a neighbor who had observed four people entering the building.
The four were immediately arrested.
