Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome announces details of the aircraft accident in which government secretary Francisco Blake and another seven people were killed.
The Secretaría de Comunicaciones y Transporte - SCT (Secretary of Communications and Transport in Mexico) informed that the results of the investigation of the accident in which government secretary Francisco Blake Mora and another seven people were killed indicate that the helicopter with its whole intact structure has collided directly against the ground without the pilot being able to initiate an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed before take-off that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller blades had contact with trees at 25 meters height, with the helicopter losing the fuselage, seems to indicate that the helicopter had had several ground contacts."
He also stated that the helicopter was built for 19 inmates, which is why it met all the requirements for the transport of personnel.
He also said that no helicopter parts were found during the investigations in the area where the machine was run down.
"In the search no aircraft parts were found at other places, the impact affected the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 passengers, which is why it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has a slope of 7 to 30 degrees.
At the moment it is a priority to get the results as soon as possible, but it could take several months, perhaps even a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, General Director of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretary for Aircraft and Relief Services in Mexico), assured that the helicopter from the Estado Mayor Presidencial had flown at cruising speed and the aircraft had fallen to a soft slope.
"This information strengthens the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of impact."
At a press conference, the head of SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant points that should be taken into account in the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with the flight standards, it was a flight according to the rules of visual flight. This means that the crew must have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded suitable weather conditions at take-off. During the onward flight towards the border area between Mexico City and the Mexico State, some low-hanging clouds rose.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that the team had chosen a lower area with better visibility towards the Cuernavaca valley because of the clouds.
Impact point:
The collision coordinates and the last radar record of the helicopter are identical. There may have been neither a loss of control over the aircraft nor a deviation from the flight route before the collision.
Dispersal of the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available to date indicates that the helicopter had collided from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of the scattered remnants of aircraft suggests that the helicopter had hit the ground with its intact structure.
No evidence of fire or explosion:
The remains of the aircraft do not indicate fire or explosion at the scene of the accident.
The latest results indicate several ground contacts.
During the on-site investigations, aircraft parts were found at an altitude of 9200 feet above sea level. The terrain is sloping and has a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter was probably broken.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had several ground contacts.
After a minute search in an area that went beyond the blocked area at the scene of the accident, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, which reinforces the assumption that the unharmed aircraft structure had bounced against the ground.
MSS announces a research protocol on finding the gene for obesity
She is the head of a research project on the discovery of the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, which is supported by specialists from the IPN.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Mexico Social Insurance Institute) announced that it is leading a research project on the discovery of the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and youth", with which the genetic markers are to be found in connection with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, Focus on Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI stated that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutrition specialists and social workers was built.
This team is supported by specialists and students of the postgraduate course at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested parties can come to the IMSS sports grounds in the valley of Mexico, where tests with children and adolescents are carried out every Saturday from 8 a.m.
He stressed that the investigation began on the sports field of Cuauhtémoc (in the west of the state of México) and continued on the sports field of Nezahualcóyolt (in the east of the state of México) since 8 October.
Once the target of 500 to 600 investigators has been reached, the study will be continued on the sports field of Independencia (in the south of the capital district) and completed on the one of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He stated that the aim of the study was to learn about the factors and role of genetics in connection with the development of obesity and the identification of risk factors for Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the global diabetes day, he said that three thousand children and adolescents aged six to 14 should fill out nutritional questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They are also asked questions about their physical activity and family history in order to control risk factors that could lead to diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He also stated that on the aforementioned Saturdays the subjects were measured (weight, size, waist size), their blood pressure and blood values such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (trying to identify genes related to childhood obesity).
Cruz López stressed that this investigation would be carried out on the occasion of the concern of health workers about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"The health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in just under six years, the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent. Obesity also increased dramatically," stressed the specialist of the IMSS.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of Mexico's population differed from that of other peoples.
He stated that a (e) Mexican (in) is on average 65 percent of Indian-American descent, 30 percent of European descent, and 5 percent of African descent, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
In general, he explained that the genetics of obesity are expressed in the inability to burn the excess of the energy (calories) we consume, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants was a comprehensive study of the children, which would determine whether they had a degree of obesity or obesity.
It would even investigate the occurrence of dark skin wrinkles in the neck and inner arm (akanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and pre-stage diabetes.
All information will be kept confidential and communicated to parents in writing by the doctors. The doctors will explain to parents all the results of the measurements and propose to them changes in lifestyle that are appropriate for the prevention of diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three fundamental factors responsible for obesity, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, that is, lack of exercise in everyday life, spending most of the day in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
The high calorie intake, i.e. an increased consumption of sugared drinks and carbohydrates (Tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.), along with a high intake of fat and protein, as well as the genetics to be analyzed in this research project.
Asphalt from UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM, develops polymer-modified asphalt to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs from the pavement were to be observed, it would not be necessary to repair almost 200 000 potholes when the rainy season breaks out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (Mexico Valley City Area), Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, warned and assured that if the laying and maintenance of the asphalt surface were properly damaged, the number of potholes would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Troughholes from a Technical Perspective", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing polymer-modified asphalt to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Mr. Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the road surface and thus avoid the occurrence of potholes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound of which one part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphaltenes - and the other part a low - the so-called Malthene. Together they give the road surface its characteristic viscous elastic behaviour.
Elastic behaviour of the asphalt means that at high temperatures of almost 180°C it behaves like a liquid, at 120°C it is very viscous and almost solid at 50°C, while it becomes fragile at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," said the chemical engineer.
The researcher of the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City had a majority of flexible pavements, composed of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a wear layer of asphalt consisting of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer had been bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on and produce forces, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemical engineer.
"On top of the wear layer," he said, "a final layer is laid out, the so-called bearing layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they have to produce friction.
In addition, the load-bearing layer needs an adequate thickness and the material it consists of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, especially the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes wet, water penetrates into the layer and is difficult to escape again. This causes a softening of all layers of the road surface and consequently the occurrence of potholes.
When a pothole is created," he said, "the cover layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only damaged afterwards. But the damage does not occur immediately, but is a process that must be repaired by appropriate maintenance programs at the first signs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) stated that the vehicle load is another important cause for the occurrence of potholes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be proportional to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with in order to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that a lot of research was still to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries, and with which the potholes could be repaired easily and without the use of high temperatures.
