So was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A lophoscopeist from Cali entered history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials plays a key role.
Last November 4, a Lophoscopeist of the Criminal Investigation Unit (CTI) from Cali, who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia - Revolutionary Forces of Colombia), went into action: "Alfonso Cano" by comparing the fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopeists in the CTI department, this week Eliazar González was on standby, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working on criminal investigations for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in communities in Chocó, where he often had to go into the jungle for five days to reach the place where the bodies he was supposed to identify were located.
In 2000 he moved to Valle and after completing the required courses he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin that is exposed to friction, i.e. the palms of the hands and feet.
During the week of the campaign against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was advised to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
Friday night he flew in the helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew that he should identify two bodies, and that there was a suspicion that one of the man who had led the oldest guerrilla in the world could be. Therefore, he should take with him the ten-finger print sheet of Guillermo León Sáenz (his actual name).
However, when he reached with the examiner the place where the body was located, he could not identify him due to his physical appearance, for this did not resemble the images he had seen in the mass media in the slightest.
He had no beard, was dressed like a farmer in the area, wore no glasses and was much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, plant ladle, and flashlight, Eliazar compared the body's fingerprints to those on the print sheet.
He had seen it right: It was Alfonso Cano.
The same night, this man from Puerto Tejada was responsible for telling the Minister of Defence, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was actually the head of the FARC.
Searching for clues
For a dactyloscope from the Sijín in Cali, the tribute given to President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar González at a press conference on the use of "cano" was very important.
Many people do not know our work.
The dactyloscopy is an exact science without error rate, which can be a key factor in the resolution of a crime.
Lophoscopeists not only identify corpses, they also support investigations into murder and robbery and confirm the identity of the arrested persons.
When they are arrested, many offenders submit false identity papers or have none.
We'll take the fingerprints off them and find them in the database.
The researcher told us that during a theft he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house, because the thief had supported himself with his hand right here when he pulled out a safe stuffed with jewelry and money.
"Wounds are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for fingerprinting, but in this case we could take the print of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in several thefts," he recalled.
The fingerprints can also be used to relieve or burden murder suspects.
Recently, a dead man was found surrounded by liquor bottles.
In the investigation, it was suspected that a family member might be suspect, and actually a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that it is the murderer, he is nevertheless associated with the place where the crime was committed.
A Dactyloscopician of the CTI stated that "the fingerprints were taken from the object with chemical or physical reagents."
When they appear, a plant ladle or ribbon is used to take them away.
After that, the prints are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the civil status office.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without identity papers," the expert from the CTI explained.
He said that not everything was as depicted in the TV series SCI.
Just as not all gold that shines isn't all you touch, a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if you make a corresponding comparison.
