Energy policy:
Facts should prevail over dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or emotions, this is certainly energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to take an election meeting as an opportunity to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it explores all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is driving a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, an enormous proportion of the world's population should not have to renounce a vital element.
At the same time, it is necessary to mitigate the shortage of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity constantly, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to fight against climatic irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains isolated in its decision to forego nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which submits its decision to the need to find a substitute source capable of substitution, nor in Switzerland, which just intends to build nuclear power plants of the last generation.
Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name but a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
After Fukushima, the United States, for its part, decided to add another unit to their park by restarting the Three Mile Island plant, which was shut down after the nuclear accident.
Even if the German model, which is geared to renewable energy sources, is occasionally presented as an example, reality contradicts the discourse.
The election in Berlin will take the form of an increase in the price of electricity, an increase in energy dependence, especially on Russia, as a result of the increased use of imported gas, and an increase in CO2 emissions caused by gas and coal-fired power plants.
The totality of these unpleasant effects will already be felt within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives rise to reflection.
Denmark is, on the one hand, the European leader in the table on wind energy, from which it obtains 30% of its electricity, and, on the other hand, the country is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, alternately used with wind energy; as a result, its CO2 emissions and electricity prices are 65% and 50% respectively higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the stability of our energy policy, our neighbours pay 40% higher electricity bills than our French households.
Since the price of energy in the globalised economy is a key element of competitiveness and a guarantee of stability for industry on national soil, French companies have an advantage due to the most favourable electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore lead to a strong increase in energy prices, which would make the noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys showed that this is a price that the vast majority of French people are just as unwilling to pay as it shows resistance to the principle of this energy source.
Let us bear in mind that our country's energy policy has made it possible to build an industry with 125,000 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a plethora of specialised small and medium-sized enterprises to the international markets and makes them the creators of countless jobs.
If France decided to phase out nuclear power, most of these SMEs would fall victim to it, and the annual EUR 6 billion in exports of capital goods and nuclear energy would shrink more and more.
Which electrician would commission an EPR designed to work for sixty years if the decline of his producer is preprogrammed?
In order to solve the energetic equation, one must admit that there is no more a miracle tool for generating electricity than a devil's work.
The low-carbon solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy are proof of the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a security authority that carries out uncompromising and transparent controls in existing plants, such as the construction in Flamanville.
Their work teams, who have made a name for themselves because of their professionalism, are just too obsessed with the safety concept.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious incidents.
Only a single one, in Three Mile Island, has occurred under normal operating conditions, so it ran without consequences for man and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was conjured up by reactor construction and infinite human error.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented proportions that caused the death of several ten thousand people.
The nuclear industry will draw its lessons from this accident just as it did after the previous two.
As a fruit of this approach and of cooperation between the safety authorities of the French and German operators and designers of nuclear power plants, the EPR represents a design that enables it to withstand such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable among the electrical engineers to build a nuclear power plant, a construction stop in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition of Areva and EDF by allowing them to take the lead in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is essential and legitimate to look for the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and party leaders dominate a debate that also determines the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy led by Nicolas Sarkozy was criticized from many angles - overloading police, judicial and administrative bodies due to a numerical policy, compatibility of this policy with the status of a "country of human rights", as France had titled itself.
Recently, the harassment directed against foreign students from the official side had shaped the weekly shows, the Interior Minister had casually (see Libération of 23 May) announced that France "had no talent, bricklayers or waiters from abroad needed".
But this policy has rarely been analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the right and the left.
On the right hand side, the tone of Jacques Chirac, who had declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed, including over 2 million immigrant workers, should not be a problem for a country", from the left side by Michel Rocard, who had stated in 1990 that France "cannot absorb all the world's poverty".
The only difference is the degree of generosity
Fear of the invasion of national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was divided from both right and left in 2005.
Both camps perceived immigrants as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that one is willing to admit to immigrants.
Francois Hollande, in his programme, confines himself to banalities which point out that development in partnership allows us to solve our "migration problems".
This notion of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may affect the elections; however, it is economically costly.
As economic experts Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron present to us in a recent work summarizing the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of the flood of immigrants on economic growth, wages and jobs in the immigration countries.
Limiting immigration would undermine growth and damage the labour market situation.
The fears about the influence of migrants are based on the idea that they are threatening to substitute the local labour force, especially the lower-skilled, by exerting pressure on their wages.
However, experience shows that immigrants are, in fact, much more complementary than domestic wage-earners, since they are mainly engaged in occupations in sectors which are technically unencumbered.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local wage earners, the more skilled among the immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not aligned with labour supply.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a lack of anesthesiologists, this complementarity also causes a positive effect of immigrant migration on wages and the national labour market.
Giovanni Peri has calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the influx of immigrants would result in an inclusive, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of ideas introduced by immigrants as well as economic growth is beneficial (high proportion of naturalised immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to social systems, on average around 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organisation estimates, for example, that a person who immigrates to Germany at the age of 30 will, on average, contribute a net contribution (revenue minus expenditure) of around EUR 150,000 to the public budget over his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wished to bring about the missing intersections "with the teeth" at the beginning of his mandate.
However, these said teeth, which should deter immigrants, achieved exactly the opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, now it remains to think through European democracy
Democracy is a valuable asset; it is also a delicate asset.
The European continent should be able to remember for itself who, after its invention in Athens more than two thousand years ago, had let the entire 20th century pass over the tragedies of the First World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Francos in Spain, Salazars in Portugal and the Supreme in Greece.
Some had believed that it was enough to exercise the right to vote, in the most direct way possible, to see democracy prevail over their enemies once and for all.
One knows since Napoleon "the little one" that it was a characteristic of the mental attitude.
The general right to vote, the necessary condition of democracy, is not a sufficient condition for this and can just as well become an "oppression instrument", as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot put it at the time.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, separation and control of powers, an education, education, economic and social community spirit, a jurisprudence.
The crisis in Europe we are in is an economic crisis, but it is just as much and first and foremost a political and democratic crisis.
The change of attitude of the Greek True-False referendum would have had a double enlightening character in this regard: the need for a powerful return of politics, but also the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its inappropriateness.
This ambivalence should be considered obsolete.
The truth is that the front lines of democratic struggle have shifted today, and that the Republican soldiers, or at least most of them, are no longer aiming in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain to push for a success of the national referendum, which was organized in accordance with the needs and in wrong order.
A free pass for the European sole ruler or a blind jump into the void of nationalistic withdrawal: a great choice for the citizen!
No, we want Hackebeil, but a collective task, from full right, settled and steady, an election and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain and Portugal - it is no longer clear where to end the list - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is all Europe that is bowing to the dictates of markets and credit rating agencies, suffering from its powerlessness and lack of solidarity.
It is all Europe that is humiliated at international level.
We are concerned about transfers of sovereignty towards Europe - it is all Europe which is gradually losing its sovereignty, and thus every single one of the nations attached to it.
The urgency is to give back to popular sovereignty the leadership of the European project.
It is a matter of the whole of whether Europeans can reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from the markets and launch a future through investment.
The exit from the crisis has decisions at European level as a condition, which cannot be made without total democratic legality, without certainly leading us to ruin.
After a long time of fighting this proposal by Jacques Delors and the Socialists, everyone today is pushing European economic governance.
Agreed.
But without political integration and a stronger democracy - as it suggests to the citizens - this would be a new folly and a further impasse.
We must take on a new stage in European integration.
In order to create the republic in France, it was necessary to "create" Republicans.
The revolution of interests alone could not do enough here.
This teaching remains valid.
We must form a more integrated Europe at economic level.
This can only be achieved by creating a politically more democratic Europe, a truly European people's sovereignty.
We need Europeans to create Europe.
"Contactless" chip cards become general goods
The World Chip Card Fair opens its doors on Tuesday in Villepinte near Paris in an optimistic attitude.
According to Eurossmart, 2011 was supposed to end with a 11% increase in global sales of microprocessor chips (EC cards, SIM card phones), with more than 6 billion units sold.
The most important segment is the contactless technology that allows payments on public transport or payment of purchases by simply holding the card to a reader.
Compared to the 320 million sold a year earlier, 460 million contactless smart cards would be sold worldwide this year!
Their market share should increase further in 2012 (580 million units expected) and represent over 10% of the global chip card market (6,925 million cards).
Europe is gaining ground in terms of contactless payment, having been lagging behind the Asia-Pacific region for a long time.
Some 26 million Visa cards are already equipped with this functionality, and 75,000 payment terminals accept it.
In France, the beginnings are rather modest: only 400,000 contactless visa cards have been distributed.
Consumer markets, however, are steaming up.
Carrefour has therefore issued 2.5 million contactless pass MasterCards this year.
In order to move to a higher speed, it is now necessary for banks to equip their customers with these cards.
"Two major French financial institutions have committed themselves to systematically handing out bank cards with contactless chips to their customers in the future," announces Gérard Nébouy, Director General of Visa Europe France.
Banks test payment by mobile phone
However, this is only a first step on the way to the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
To date, a tiny percentage of devices have been equipped with NFC (Near Field Communication) technology necessary to carry out these transactions.
"They're in delay".
"But they should at least experience a real upward trend next year."
"In 2012, we expect to sell 80 to 120 million units worldwide," explains Marc Bertin, Chairman of Eurosmart.
But the banks are taking the initiative.
The Crédit Agricole announced yesterday the launch of a test run in Caen, which will run from December to next June.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and employees are to be equipped with a capsule that allows contactless payment.
BPCE operates a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And also the Société Générale had yesterday declared to prepare the launch of an offer that allows their customers contactless payment by mobile phone.
Terrorist Front understands itself, from the Sahara to Nigeria
Paris is concerned about the relations between al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The long suspected relationship between the terrorist group al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram seems to confirm.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel himself confirmed that Algiers had now acquired "certainty".
"The way in which both organizations operate, as well as the relations of the secret services, indicate clear cooperation," he said without going further into detail.
Paris seems to be doing a similar analysis.
The investigation of the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January had exposed interfaces.
Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory, kidnapped by supporters of the Aqmi in a restaurant in Niamey, are said to have been killed the following day at the same time as several of their hijackers during an operation carried out by the French Special Forces.
French and Nigerian investigators want to have found several phone chips belonging to the terrorists in the rubble at the scene of the operation.
Terrorist axis
The analysis of the telephone calls led to several interlocutors stationed in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), investigators are particularly interested in the numbers of two interlocutors: one leads to a Nigerian who has long been in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria that had stopped the cradle of Boko Haram; the other leads to a man considered close to the Aqmi and the sect.
"This is a step forward, but there is no doubt that we need to wait for clearer evidence before we can talk about an operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Harem".
"It's conceivable, though".
"For years, it has been known that the sect has attracted financial and intellectual support from outside and that it is becoming increasingly active," says Nigerian researcher Kunle Amuwo.
In recent months, these "support services" have become increasingly visible in their course, as well as the speeches and operational modes of Boko Harem, which now indicate the involvement of suicide bombers and the use of increasingly complex explosives, which bear the same signature as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, to start with Washington, has since then been exerting pressure on Abuja to take account of the problems caused by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities have indeed for a long time regarded the group as a community of Illuminati, to which no special attention needs to be paid.
Faster success
Boko Haram, founded in 2002 in Maiduguri near a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist Iman Mohammed Yusuf - which in Haoussa means "Western education is a disgrace" - is pursuing the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this destitute region, the merger is experiencing rapid success.
It politicizes itself and demands strict observance of the Shariah, while the activists attached to it fight against the godless central government.
The activists initially target churches, bars and authorities.
In 2009, Boko Haram activists were particularly active in their intensified attacks against the commissioners.
However, Abuja's reaction is as usual indifferent.
The army surrounds the city, counting 800 dead.
The imprisoned Mohammed Yusuf is killed in prison.
As a result, the sect is becoming increasingly radical and leaving its strongholds in the north.
Last Christmas she confessed to an attack in Jos, which claimed 80 lives, then to another one in Abuja.
In June, Boko Haram is blamed for a suicide attack that occurred in the secure police headquarters in Abuja - the first of its kind.
In August, the United Nations local headquarters became the primary international target.
Since then, the formation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which is to lead from Mauritania to Nigeria to Somalia, has troubled all security experts.
While the Aqmi has occupied Mali and Niger, the Somalis of al-Shabaab operate in Kenya, Boko Harem seems to be a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, during a conversation with President Goodluck Jonathan in Nigeria,ta Alain Juppé warned against Boko Harem and showed himself ready to "communicate all clues".
